{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620082"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:39:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:39:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16609"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16609"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.09,0.06,0.06,0.73]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9300"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68910"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9300"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16609"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54367"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5252"},{"type":"tags","id":"5253"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22021"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23106"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68910"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is diagnosed with HER2-positive breast cancer. Her oncologist recommends treatment with trastuzumab, explaining that it is a monoclonal antibody specifically designed to target the HER2 protein on cancer cells. Monoclonal antibodies have a key characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the key characteristic?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bind to multiple different antigens simultaneously","Change binding specificity over time","Generated from polyclonal B cell responses","Produced by multiple different B cell clones","Target a single specific epitope"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMonoclonal antibodies are characterised by their ability to \u003Cstrong\u003Etarget a single specific epitope\u003C/strong\u003E on an antigen. This specificity comes from their production from a single B cell clone, ensuring all antibody molecules are identical and bind to the same epitope. In the case of trastuzumab, this epitope is on the HER2 protein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinding to multiple different antigens simultaneously\u003C/strong\u003E describes polyclonal antibodies rather than monoclonal antibodies. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneration from polyclonal B cell responses\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as monoclonal antibodies are produced from a single B cell clone. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBeing \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduced by multiple different B cell clones\u003C/strong\u003E would result in polyclonal antibodies with varying specificities. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe concept that antibodies \u003Cstrong\u003Echange binding specificity over time\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as monoclonal antibodies maintain constant specificity throughout their use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe high specificity of monoclonal antibodies makes them valuable therapeutic tools, allowing precise targeting of disease-related molecules while minimising off-target effects. This is particularly important in cancer therapy where specific targeting of cancer cells is desired.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Monoclonal antibodies are engineered proteins that specifically target and bind to a single epitope on an antigen.","The suffix \u0027-mab\u0027 indicates a monoclonal antibody drug, with prefixes indicating source (e.g., \u0027-xi-\u0027 for chimeric, \u0027-zu-\u0027 for humanised).","Monoclonal antibodies can work through multiple mechanisms including blocking receptors, targeting cells for destruction, or neutralising proteins."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54367"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16609"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54367"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T17:03:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T17:04:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9300"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68910"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self"